textfield.text: Multithreading Basics

Multitasking The ability to have more than one program working at what seems like the same time. For ex. Print a document while editing an mail. Multithreading A program/process can have several light weight threads that run concurrently to perform different tasks. Programs that run more than one thread are called multi-threaded programs.
Multitasking and Multithreading
Advantages of Multithreading

Process versus Thread. Advantages of multithreading over multitasking Threads share the data so inter-thread communication is efficient. Threads are lightweight. Threads share the same address space so they save the memory. Context switching between threads is usually less expensive than between processes. Improve performance of an application.

Threads are the tasks that belong to a program and can run ‘simultaneously’. On a single CPU, each competing thread is given a slice of time to perform its task. The faster context switch simulates concurrency. On multi-processor system, the threads (processes) may actually run in parallel on different CPUs. main method runs in one thread called main thread.
What is a thread?

Two approaches to create a thread Extending the java.lang.Thread class, overriding run method (thread logic) and creating a thread by calling start method. Create a thread object by passing a runnable task in java.lang.Thread constructor. A task is nothing but an implementation of java.lang.Runnable interface. Lets see these two different approaches before having some discussion on thread VS Runnable.
Creating a thread

Thread Basics
Thread states New State Runnable State (Ready to run state + running state) Blocked Waiting Timed waiting Terminated
Thread Life Cycle
Thread lifecycle Thread state transition Thread Synchronization Locking in Multithreaded environment
Key Learning Outcomes

Terminated State In this state thread is dead. Thread can not be rerun. Invocation of run method throws exception. Achieved By The completion of run method. Uncaught exception thrown in the run method and is not handled.
Thread Life Cycle (contd..)

Waiting State When thread waits for other thread to notify. It happens when Object.wait() or Object.join() method is called. No timeout parameter is specified. Difference between blocked and waiting state is not significant. Timed Waiting State Threads can sleep for a given time by calling a method that takes timeout as parameter. Waiting time is controlled by timeout parameter. State persists either until timeout expires or the appropriate notification has been received. Important methods with timeout parameter – Thread.sleep, Object.wait, Thread.join
Thread Life Cycle (contd..)

Runnable State (Running) As per Oracle specification, ‘Running’ is not a separate state. It’s part of Runnable. Thread is currently executing. A thread achieves running state when a scheduler selects a thread from runnable pool. Thread’s run method is executing. Blocked State Temporarily inactive. Blocked for lock acquisition. Blocked on I/O. Blocked for Join completion. Resource required for the thread are locked by another thread.
Thread Life Cycle (contd..)

New state Thread instance is created. Start method has not been invoked. Thread is considered not alive. Some bookkeeping is required before a thread can run. Runnable State (Ready to Run State) start method is invoked. A thread is waiting for its turn on the processor. Can return to this state from blocked, waiting and timed waiting states.
Thread Life Cycle (contd..)

Synchronization helps to control the access to the shared resources/data in multi-threaded environment. Synchronize the method where atomic operations are required. Calling a synchronized method attempts to acquire the lock on the object. If lock is available, it is acquired If not available then this thread is placed in the entry set for the lock A class can have both synchronized and non synchronized methods. Classes can’t be synchronized.

Two or more threads need to share the resources/data. What if two threads try to modify the same data? This results in corrupted objects – The situation called as Race Condition.
Race Condition

Yield in English means – Give over, supply, surrender to other. Causes the currently executing thread to yield. The highest priority thread from the runnable pool will be chosen by the schedule to run. It is a static method of Thread class. Don’t rely on yield or thread priority for correctness of your program.
Yield

Every thread has a priority. Its values can be from 1-10 as defined in Thread class. Priority values defined in Thread class MIN_PRIORITY: 1 NORMAL_PRIORITY : 5 MAX_PRIORITY: 10 By default every thread inherits the priority of the thread that constructed it. Thread priorities are highly system dependent. Thread scheduler prefers a thread with highest priority to run but it’s not guaranteed.
Thread Priorities

It is the part of JVM which decides which thread should run at a given moment. Any thread in the runnable pool can be chosen by the scheduler to run. Different threads can have different priorities. Scheduler prefers (not guaranteed) to run a thread with higher priority. We don’t have direct control on the scheduler but we can influence its behavior. Java provides APIs for this purpose.
Thread Scheduler

Concurrency Framework

Lock is taken on the object (not on the method). Once a thread acquires the lock on an object, no other thread can enter any synchronized method in that class. If a class has both synchronized and non-synchronized methods, multiple threads can still access non-synchronized methods at the same time. You can also synchronize a piece of block rather than a method.
Synchronization (Contd..)

Methods of Object class. Must be called from synchronized context. Used for inter-thread communication. Wait Makes the current thread wait. notify Used to wake up the waiting thread. Wakes up a single thread (chosen randomly). notifyAll Used to wake up waiting threads. Wakes up all the threads waiting to get lock.
Inter thread communication (wait, notify and notifyAll)

The current thread sleeps for specified time period (in milli seconds). It guarantees that thread is going to sleep for specified time period but does not guarantee that it will wake up and start running once the specified time elapses. Throws InterruptedException if interrupted. No need to call in synchronized context. If called from synchronized context, lock is not released.

If a thread goes to sleep, it holds any lock it has. A thread can acquire more than one lock. Synchronization is an overhead, it retards the performance of the application so it should be avoided (not at the cost of functionality). Synchronized block should be preferred over synchronized methods.
Synchronization (Contd..)

sleep Thread stops execution. used to make the thread sleep for a specified time so that other threads get CPU time. wait Thread stops execution. Is used to relinquish lock. After release of lock thread enters waiting state. Other threads competing for the lock get a chance to acquire the lock. Waiting threads need to be notified to make them runnable.

Deadlock
Allows one thread to wait for the completion of another. Throws InterruptedException if interrupted.
Join

Occurs when two threads are blocked, with each waiting for other’s lock. Neither can run until other releases lock, so they’ll wait forever. To avoid the dead lock, lock should be acquired in predefined manner. There is nothing in Java to avoid the deadlocks. Design your program in such a way that deadlock situation can’t occur.

Java provides volatile keyword for synchronized access to instance field. Threads update the instance fields in local cache. That change may not reflect to other threads. Every read and write of a volatile variable takes place from the main memory.

You can control the life of the thread pool by calling shutdown() method of Executor Service. If a thread pool is no more required, it should be shutdown. ExecutorService.shutdown() method initiates an orderly shutdown in which previously submitted tasks are executed. If shutdown method has been called on a pool, no new task is accepted. A runtime exception java.util.concurrent.RejectedExecutionException is thrown. Invocation of this method has no additional effect if the pool is already shut down.

Concurrency framework provide its own implementations of thread pools. Different types of thread pools can be used in different requirements. Concurrency Framework has different thread pool implementations based on different requirements. Fixed Thread Pool Cached Thread Pool Single Thread Pool Scheduled Thread Pool
Concurrency Framework Thread Pool

Java Concurrency framework was introduced in java version 1.5. Doug Lea, a professor of computer science at State University of New York, developed the concurrency framework and chaired JSR 166, which added concurrency utilities to the Java programming language. Java 1.4 Multithreading uses the locking mechanism by using synchronized keyword. Synchronization comes up with a cost of locking and waiting. Instead of using synchronized keyword concurrency framework uses CAS (compare and Swap) algorithm. CAS is an OS level algorithm which do not need a lock on object or classes. Either we acquire a lock on object or we acquire a lock on a class in Java 1.4 multithreading. But we can also achieve method level lock in concurrency framework. In Java 1.4 Multithreading, if a lock is acquired in a thread, it is released in the same thread (Scope of locking is one synchronized block). But we can acquire a lock in thread T1 and release the lock in thread T2 by using java concurrency framework. This feature leads minimal number of deadlocks.

newCachedThreadPool() Creates new threads as needed. Reuses previously constructed thread if available. If no existing threads available, new thread is created and added to the pool. Threads not used for sixty seconds are terminated and removed from cache. Pool that remains idle for long enough will not consume any resources.
Executors (Contd..)

newSingleThreadExecutor() Single working thread Tasks are guaranteed to execute sequentially, and no more than one task will be active at any given time. If this single thread terminates due to a failure during execution prior to shutdown, a new one will take its place if needed to execute subsequent tasks.
Executors (Contd..)

newFixedThreadPool(int nThreads) Creates a fixed number of threads. Takes number of fixed threads as input. Number of tasks submitted are more than number of idle threads than tasks placed in queue . Threads are created on the need basis. A thread pool of size 3 will create 2 threads if 2 tasks has been submitted.
Executors (Contd..)

Creating new threads is expensive operation. What if we like to keep a limit on the maximum number of concurrent threads? Solution – Thread Pools. Thread pool maintains threads and provides threads as they are needed Threads in a thread pool do not die, once the task assigned to them is complete, they are back in thread pool and wait for the next task to be assigned
Thread Pool

A Future is nothing but a monitor to a task. Future reference provides the control over a task. You can cancel the task, can check the status of the task, can get the result returned by callable task etc.

In java 1.4, If a lock has acquired on an object/class, no other thread can acquire the lock on the same object/class. Also ,the scope of the critical section is synchronized block. In concurrency framework, lock is not acquired on object/class. Two different thread can enter in critical section. Semaphores are often used to restrict the number of threads that can access some (physical or logical) resource. Semaphore maintains a count of the permits available and acts accordingly. Semaphore.acquire reduces the permit count by 1 and Semaphore.release() increase the permit count by 1. Semaphore.acquire () is blocking call if the permit count of the semaphore is 0.

“At lease 4 vehicles are passed across this point”. You can find this statement when you travel at hill areas. Barriers of concurrency framework also works on the same approach. Concurrency framework’s cyclic barriers are useful in programs involving a fixed sized party of threads that must occasionally wait for each other. The barrier is called cyclic because it can be re-used after the waiting threads are released.

A service that decouples the production of new asynchronous tasks from the consumption of the results of completed tasks. Producers submit tasks for execution. Consumers take completed tasks and process their results in the order they complete. A CompletionService can for example be used to manage asynchronous IO, in which tasks that perform reads are submitted in one part of a program or system, and then acted upon in a different part of the program when the reads complete, possibly in a different order than they were requested. ExecutorCompletionService is the implementation of this interface.
